@Carrboro Jim -- it's a jumble or medley of things, or (in cooking) a hash or ragout with minced meat. It's actually 'gallimaufry', but I threw an extra U in there to Gallicize it.

The etymology goes back to the Old French of the mid 1500s 'galer' (to have fun) and 'mafrer' (to eat large amounts) as spoken in Picardy, resulting in 'galimafree' (an unappetizing dish)

Its usage (though still low) seems to have doubled in the last century, perhaps due to people making more use of the bits of leftovers accumulating in their refrigerators.

